# Veversal Beta Deploy Rule

## Never mark beta task complete after git push alone

Push to main ≠ live on beta. Beta updates only when Deploy Beta workflow succeeds OR manual `deploy_beta.sh` succeeds.

## After every commit+push that should reach beta

1. Check GitHub Actions:
   - Backend: `gh run list --repo PeterM358/vhr-backend --workflow=deploy-beta.yml --limit 3`
   - Frontend (if relevant): `gh run list --repo PeterM358/vhr-frontend --workflow=deploy-beta.yml --limit 3`
2. If user asked for deploy, wait for or verify green run.
3. If failed, report exact error from `gh run view <id> --log-failed` and give recovery:
   `cd /opt/veversal/backend && git pull && bash deploy/deploy_beta.sh`
4. Tell user which commits should now be on beta (`git log -1`).

## Single deploy path

- Full stack deploy: `deploy/deploy_beta.sh` on server (pulls BOTH backend + frontend, docker, build).
- Both repos have Deploy Beta workflow SSHing to server; workflow **git syncs backend before running the script**.
- Server `flock -w` serializes deploys across repos; `cancel-in-progress: true` cancels stale in-repo runs when commits land seconds apart.

## Deploy script location

- Backend repo: `/opt/veversal/backend/deploy/deploy_beta.sh`
- Run: `bash deploy/deploy_beta.sh` (executable in git)

## When backend AND frontend changed

- Push both repos.
- One successful deploy run updates both — do not SSH twice manually.

## Agent completion checklist

- [ ] git status clean, committed, pushed
- [ ] GitHub Actions Deploy Beta green (or user notified to run manual deploy)
- [ ] Mention both repo commits if both changed
